    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 16 with a high-floor offensive outlook, headlined by **Yordan Alvarez**, whose projected 62.11 score makes him the premier play of the day. Despite an assumed #2 slot and a modest -10% SP skill adjustment against Juan Mejia, **Yordan Alvarez** remains a locked-in start, anchored by an impressive 0.393 xwOBA that suggests he is primed to break out against a mediocre rotation arm. Following closely is **Gary Sanchez**, who earns a 59.74 score while drawing a favorable matchup against Corbin; the combination of a significant +10% SP skill boost and a high-leverage cleanup spot against a lefty makes **Gary Sanchez** our most efficient power source for today\u2019s slate. **Junior Caminero** also projects well (58.12) as a strong start, maintaining his productivity despite a moderate penalty against Leasure.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the morning involved **Josh Smith**, who sits on the bench with a 38.31 efficiency score, narrowly missing the 40.0 \"Zebras Floor\" threshold. While a +10% park factor offered a slight glimmer of hope, the combination of a -15% dynamic platoon hit against the lefty Lopez and an unfavorable #8 spot in the order relegated him to the pine. Elsewhere, our lineup construction remains fluid; **Dillon Dingler** is a solid play at 56.12 due to the platoon advantage, but he bears watching for late-inning defensive substitutions. We are currently navigating the absences of **Trea Turner**, **Kyle Schwarber**, and **Christian Yelich**, leaving us lean on speed and power as we look to capitalize on **Chase Meidroth**\u2019s lineup stability and **Kazuma Okamoto**\u2019s reliable presence at first base to keep our 5x5 Roto metrics trending upward.",
